The proposed AMACO-QP framework introduces a pioneering healthcare-aware query optimization paradigm that integrates a multi-colony Ant Colony Optimization (ACO) algorithm with a clinically-informed cost model to facilitate scalable and credible big data analytics. Unlike traditional cost-based optimizers that prioritize purely computational metrics, this study fuses clinical priority scores, evidence-based medicine weights, and HIPAA-compliant privacy constraints to generate an optimized execution plan tailored for large-scale EHR datasets. This adaptive architecture utilizes a distributed Hadoop and Apache Spark environment for heavy-duty optimization while leveraging Presto for low-latency interactive execution, effectively bridging the gap between batch processing and real-time clinical decision support. By incorporating federated multi-colony learning and an ethical privacy-utility trade-off mechanism, the framework ensures that emergency queries are prioritized without compromising global system throughput or data security. This integrated combination of domain-specific clinical weighting, bio-inspired optimization, and multi-engine big data orchestration represents a first-of-its-kind contribution to the field of healthcare informatics and scalable query processing.
